      <p>* Steelcase's "lifetime" warranty is limited to 10 years of single-shift use — read the fine print.</p>

      <p>The Steelcase Leap V2 is the chair we recommend most often as the Aeron alternative. At $1,029 it is $466 cheaper, has the better armrests, and its LiveBack technology genuinely flexes with your spine. The tradeoff is heat — the foam seat builds up warmth over a long day, and the upholstery will show wear faster than the Aeron's Pellicle. Our full breakdown is in the <a href="/reviews/steelcase-leap-v2-review/">Leap V2 review</a>.</p>

      <p>The Embody is Herman Miller's own upgrade to the Aeron, designed by the same team behind the original Aeron. It uses a "pixelated support" layer of 139 plastic fingers instead of mesh. Some people love it; we found it gimmicky. The Aeron remains the better choice for most buyers.</p>

      <p>For a step-down option, the Branch Ergonomic Chair at $399 covers 80% of the Aeron's benefits at 27% of the price. If you are on the fence about whether you actually need a $1,495 chair, start there. We have a full <a href="/reviews/best-ergonomic-chair-under-500/">sub-$500 roundup</a> that walks through the tradeoffs.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy direct from Herman Miller if you want the full 12-year warranty and free white-glove delivery. The same warranty applies to authorized dealers like Design Within Reach and Crandall Office Furniture. Avoid gray-market sellers on eBay and Amazon Marketplace — they are often refurbished units sold as new, and Herman Miller will not honor the warranty on them.</p>

      <p>Pick PostureFit SL over standard lumbar if you have any history of back pain. The $170 upgrade pays for itself in comfort within the first month. Skip it if you are buying purely as prevention and have no current issues.</p>

      <p>Choose graphite over black if you want the chair to age gracefully. Black shows dust within a day; graphite hides it for a week. Mineral and carbon are also good neutral choices. Avoid the brighter colors unless your office is already designed around them — they date quickly.</p>

      <p>Skip the casters upgrade. The standard carpet casters are fine on hard floors with a mat, and the felt casters Herman Miller sells for hard floors are overpriced. We use third-party rollerblade-style casters from Amazon that glide smoother for half the cost.</p>

      <p>Finally, complete the ergonomic loop. The Aeron supports your back, but it cannot fix a poorly positioned monitor or a desk at the wrong height. Pair it with a <a href="/reviews/best-foot-rest-desk/">good foot rest</a> if your feet do not sit flat, and verify your monitor is at eye level. If your desk is too tall and your chair at the right height leaves your feet dangling, you need either a shorter desk or a height-adjustable <a href="/reviews/best-standing-desk-converter/">standing desk converter</a>.</p>

